<problem display_name="Parabola" linenum="27" tex_filename="./hw/hw1.tex" showanswer="finished" attempts="3" rerandomize="per_student">
  <text>
    <p>
Is there a quadratic equation of the form [mathjaxinline]y = a + bx + cx^2[/mathjaxinline] satisfied by the four points [mathjaxinline](-2,11), (0,4), (1,2),[/mathjaxinline] and [mathjaxinline](2,1)[/mathjaxinline]? </p>
    <p>
Enter the correct formula in the form a + b*x + c*x^2 (either exactly or to two decimal places). Remember to use * for multiplication. If there is no such equation, enter the number 0. </p>
    <p>
      <p style="display:inline">[mathjaxinline]y=[/mathjaxinline] </p>
      <formularesponse inline="1" type="cs" samples="x@1:5#5" answer="4-2.5*x+0.5*x^2">
        <formulaequationinput inline="1">
          <responseparam type="tolerance" default=".01"/>
        </formulaequationinput>
      </formularesponse>
    </p>
    <p>
      <solution>
        <font color="blue">Answer: </font>
        <font color="blue">
          <p>
 For the parabola to pass through these points, we would need the following equations to be satisfied: </p>
          <table id="a0000000088" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]\begin{array}{rcccccc} 11 &amp;  = &amp;  a &amp;  - &amp;  2b &amp;  + &amp;  4c \\ 4 &amp;  = &amp;  a &amp;  + &amp;  0b &amp;  + &amp;  0c \\ 2 &amp;  = &amp;  a &amp;  + &amp;  1b &amp;  + &amp;  1c \\ 1 &amp;  = &amp;  a &amp;  + &amp;  2b &amp;  + &amp;  4c \end{array}[/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
This is a system of four linear equations in three variables [mathjaxinline]a,b,c,[/mathjaxinline] represented by the augmented matrix </p>
          <table id="a0000000089" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]\left[ \begin{array}{ccc:c} 1&amp; -2&amp; 4&amp; 11 \\ 1&amp; 0&amp; 0&amp; 4\\ 1&amp; 1&amp; 1&amp; 2\\ 1&amp; 2&amp; 4&amp; 1 \end{array} \right].[/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
 When we row-reduce this matrix, we obtain </p>
          <table id="a0000000090" class="equation" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="7" style="table-layout:auto">
            <tr>
              <td class="equation" style="width:80%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:center;border-style:hidden">[mathjax]\left[ \begin{array}{ccc:c} 1&amp; 0&amp; 0&amp; 4 \\ 0&amp; 1&amp; 0&amp; -2.5\\ 0&amp; 0&amp; 1&amp; 0.5\\ 0&amp; 0&amp; 0&amp; 0 \end{array} \right].[/mathjax]</td>
              <td class="eqnnum" style="width:20%;vertical-align:middle;text-align:left;border-style:hidden"/>
            </tr>
          </table>
          <p>
 This tells us that when [mathjaxinline]a=4, b=-2.5, c=0.5,[/mathjaxinline] the equations are all satisfied. Therefore [mathjaxinline]y=4 -2.5x + 0.5x^2[/mathjaxinline] passes through all four points. </p>
        </font>
      </solution>
    </p>
  </text>
</problem>
